Based on the provided context, the National Accountability Ordinance, 1999, and its subsequent amendments, define various offences that fall under its purview. 

According to Section 5 of the Ordinance, the following definitions are provided:

(a) "accused" shall mean a person in respect of whom there are reasonable grounds to believe that he is or has been involved in the commission of any offence triable under this Ordinance or is subject of an investigation or inquiry by the National Accountability Bureau or any other agency authorised by the National Accountability Bureau in this regard under this Ordinance;

Section 9 of the Ordinance lists the following offences:

(i) Corruption and corrupt practices;
(ii) Punishment for corruption and corrupt practice;
(iii) Misuse of power, authority, influence, nepotism, favouritism, writing off, waiving, restructuring or refinancing illegally, improperly or without sufficient justification the principal amount of loan on any financial facility, interest or mark-up on any loan or financial facility provided to any person by any bank or financial institution, a co-operative society, a Government department or an authority.

Additionally, Section 10 of the Ordinance states that the provisions of the Code of Criminal Procedure, 1860, or under any other law relating to false evidence and offences against public justice, shall apply to the trial of offences under the Ordinance.

The Schedule to the Ordinance lists the following offence and its corresponding punishment:

1. Any person who aids, abets or through any wilful act or omission is instrumental in the commission of the offence of wilful default or with wrongful intent for illegal gratification by misuse of power, authority, influence, nepotism, favouritism writes off, waives, restructures or refinances illegally, improperly or without sufficient justification the principal amount of loan on any financial facility, interest or mark-up on any loan or financial facility provided to any person by any bank or financial institution, a co-operative society, a Government department or an authority.

